						argutè.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Cleverly.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ætherea[e] dieta[e] ingenium a[e]therum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The ethereal genius of an ethereal diet.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						aptè.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Appropriately.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Theurgorum subtilis, pura, illuminata,
						et quasi angelica dia[e]ta.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The subtle, pure, illuminated, and almost angelic diet of theurgy.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Fons ingenij semper clarus, nitidusq[ue] conseruandus: quem bestia[e] solent tot sordidis
						fumis obscurare. Sic Pythagoras, et Plato, duo rari, et diuini philosophi, suos omnes
						docuerunt esse lautissimè abstinentes. Sic Apollonij Tyana[e]i, post magoru[m] secreta; 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Pythagoras"/>
					<person name="Plato"/>
					<person name="Apollonius of Tyana"/>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						singulare miraculu[m], Temperantia: virtutis radix, et ingenij fons.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The source of genius must always be kept clear and bright, which beasts usually obscure entirely with foul smoke.
				Thus Pythagoras and Plato, two rare and divine philosophers, taught all of their students to be most finely self-restrained. 
				Thus Apollonius of Tyana, after the secrets of the wise-men; Temperance is a singular miracle, 
				the root of virtue, and the source of genius. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
